04608nam a22005775i 9780822397793DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223977937 a10.1515/97808223977932doi  a(DE-B1597)552974  a(OCoLC)1229161692  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aKF4541b.B688 1999 7aLAW0600002bisacsh04a342.73/0292211 aBrandwein, Pamela, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconstructing Reconstruction :bThe Supreme Court and the Production of Historical Truth /cPamela Brandwein. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Slavery as an Interpretive Issue in the 39th Reconstruction Congress: The Northern Democrats -- t3 Republican Slavery Criticism -- t4 The Supreme Court's Official History -- t5 Dueling Histories: Charles Fairman and William Crosskey Reconstruct "Original Understanding" -- t6 Recipes for "Acceptable" History -- t7 History as an Institutional Resource: Warren Court Debates over Legislative Apportionment -- t8 Constitutional Law as a "Culture of Argument": Toward a Sociology of Constitutional Law -- t9 Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas slavery over when slaves gained formal emancipation? Was it over when the social, economic, and political situation for African Americans no longer mimicked the conditions of slavery? If the Thirteenth Amendment abolished it in 1865, why did most of the disputed points during the Reconstruction debates of 1866-75 concern issues of slavery? In this book Pamela Brandwein examines the post-Civil War struggle between competing political and legal interpretations of slavery and Reconstruction to reveal how accepted historical truth was established.Delving into the circumstances, assumptions, and rhetoric that shaped the "official" story of Reconstruction, Brandwein describes precisely how a dominant interpretation of events ultimately emerged and what its implications have been for twentieth-century judicial decisions, particularly for Supreme Court rulings on civil rights. While analyzing interpretive disputes about slavery, Brandwein offers a detailed rescoring of post-Civil War legislative and constitutional history, including analysis of the original understanding of the Fourteenth Amendment. She identifies the perspectives on Reconstruction that were endorsed or rejected by the Supreme Court. Explaining what it meant-theoretically and practically-to resolve Reconstruction debates with a particular definition of slavery, Brandwein recounts how the Northern Democratic definition of "ending" slavery was not the only definition, just the one that prevailed. Using a familiar historical moment to do new interpretive work, she outlines a sociology of constitutional law, showing how subjective narrative construction can solidify into opaque institutional memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aConstitutional historyzUnited States. 0aElection lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aReconstruction (U.S. history, 1865-1877). 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822397793zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822397793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822397793.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_D